  "prompt": "Can myopia be cured?",
  "response": "Myopia, also known as nearsightedness, is typically managed rather than cured. There are several methods to correct or manage myopia:\n\n1. **Eyeglasses and Contact Lenses**: The most common way to correct myopia is with prescription eyeglasses or contact lenses, which help focus light correctly on the retina.\n\n2. **Orthokeratology (Ortho-K)**: This involves wearing specially designed rigid gas-permeable contact lenses that temporarily reshape the cornea. These are typically worn overnight.\n\n3. **Refractive Surgery**: Procedures such as LASIK (Laser-Assisted In Situ Keratomileusis), PRK (Photorefractive Keratectomy), and SMILE (Small Incision Lenticule Extraction) can reshape the cornea to reduce or eliminate myopia.\n\n4. **Low-Dose Atropine Eye Drops**: Some studies have shown that low-dose atropine eye drops can slow the progression of myopia in children.\n\n5. **Lifestyle Changes**: Spending more time outdoors and taking breaks during prolonged periods of near work (like reading or using screens) may help reduce the progression of myopia in children.\n\nWhile these treatments can significantly improve vision or slow the progression of myopia, they do not cure the underlying condition. Research is ongoing to find more effective ways to manage and potentially cure myopia.",
